# SPEAR Framework -- Cursor Rules
#
# INSTALLATION: Copy this file to your project root as .cursorrules
# Ensure .spear/ directory exists (run: spear init).
#
# This file embeds the SPEAR methodology into Cursor's AI behavior.
# Reference: .spear/SPEAR.md for the full framework definition.

# === PHASE AWARENESS ===
# Before taking any action, determine which SPEAR phase is active.
# Check .spear/output/ to see which phase outputs exist:
#   - No spec output -> Spec phase (gather requirements, produce PRD)
#   - Spec but no plan -> Plan phase (create task plans, fitness functions)
#   - Plan but no execution report -> Execute phase (implement, test, commit)
#   - Execution report but no audit -> Audit phase (review all changes)
#   - Audit passed but no retrospective -> Ratchet phase (tighten thresholds)
#   - All complete -> New cycle (start with Spec)
#
# Never skip phases. Never execute code during Spec or Plan phases.
# Never plan during Execute phase -- follow the existing plan.

# === SPEC PHASE RULES ===
# When in Spec phase:
# 1. Read .spear/memory/ for past decisions, patterns, constraints
# 2. Read .spear/ratchet/ratchet.json for current thresholds
# 3. Ask clarifying questions before producing specs
# 4. Use templates from .spear/templates/spec/
# 5. Produce: PRD, architecture doc, epic shards
# 6. Do NOT write implementation code

# === PLAN PHASE RULES ===
# When in Plan phase:
# 1. Read approved spec outputs from .spear/output/spec/
# 2. Break work into atomic tasks with success criteria
# 3. Define fitness functions for every metric that matters
# 4. Order tasks by dependency -- no task before its prerequisites
# 5. Plan only the next phase in detail; future phases are summaries
# 6. Use templates from .spear/templates/plan/

# === EXECUTE PHASE RULES ===
# When in Execute phase:
# 1. Read the phase plan BEFORE writing any code
# 2. Read ratchet thresholds -- know the constraints
# 3. Read files before modifying them -- match existing patterns
# 4. Follow task order from the plan exactly
# 5. Atomic commits: one logical change per commit
# 6. Commit format: type(scope): description (feat/fix/refactor/test/docs/chore/perf)
# 7. Log deviations immediately if plan changes during execution
# 8. Run fitness functions at 25%, 50%, 75%, 100% checkpoints
# 9. Stop if any fitness function regresses at a checkpoint
# 10. Write tests alongside code -- never defer

# === AUDIT RULES ===
# All changes must pass 6 audit categories:
#
# 1. SECURITY (blocks on CRITICAL)
#    - No hardcoded secrets, keys, tokens, or passwords
#    - No SQL injection, XSS, CSRF vulnerabilities
#    - Input validation on all external data
#    - Auth/authz checks present where needed
#    - No error messages leaking internals
#
# 2. DEPENDENCIES (blocks on CRITICAL)
#    - New deps justified and necessary
#    - No known CVEs in added packages
#    - License compatibility verified
#    - Versions pinned in production
#
# 3. PERFORMANCE (blocks on HIGH)
#    - No O(n^2) where O(n log n) is feasible
#    - No N+1 query patterns
#    - Pagination on list endpoints
#    - Bundle/binary size justified
#
# 4. CODE QUALITY (blocks on HIGH)
#    - No code duplication (DRY)
#    - No dead code or unreachable branches
#    - Clear naming for variables, functions, types
#    - Explicit error handling -- no swallowed errors
#    - Test coverage for all new code
#    - Functions under 50 lines
#
# 5. DOCUMENTATION (blocks on CRITICAL)
#    - Public API docs for new endpoints/types
#    - README updated if behavior changed
#    - Inline comments for non-obvious logic
#
# 6. ARCHITECTURE (blocks on HIGH)
#    - No layer violations
#    - No circular dependencies
#    - Patterns consistent with existing codebase
#    - New patterns justified when existing patterns exist

# === SEVERITY LEVELS ===
# CRITICAL: Must fix. No override. Security vuln, data loss risk.
# HIGH: Fix or justify in writing. Performance regression, missing tests.
# MEDIUM: Fix in current or next cycle. Code smell, minor doc gap.
# LOW: Track. Fix when convenient. Style preference.
# INFO: Observation. No action needed.

# === RATCHET CONSTRAINTS ===
# Read .spear/ratchet/ratchet.json for current thresholds.
# Floor metrics (must stay above): test_coverage, doc_coverage
# Ceiling metrics (must stay below): max_complexity, max_bundle_size, max_build_time
# Never regress a threshold. If improvement >5%, threshold auto-tightens.
# Loosening requires written justification in ratchet/history.jsonl.

# === CODE STANDARDS ===
# - Match existing codebase patterns -- consistency over preference
# - Write tests alongside implementation, not after
# - Handle all errors explicitly -- no empty catch blocks
# - No hardcoded config values -- use config files or env vars
# - No magic numbers -- use named constants
# - Secrets never in code -- env vars or secret managers only
# - Conventional commits: type(scope): description

# === MEMORY SYSTEM ===
# Before Spec and Plan phases, read:
#   .spear/memory/decisions/ -- past Architecture Decision Records
#   .spear/memory/patterns/ -- established code patterns
#   .spear/memory/antipatterns/ -- known failures to avoid
#   .spear/memory/findings/ -- archived audit findings
#
# After Ratchet phase, write new entries to memory.

# === TEMPLATES ===
# All phase outputs must use templates from .spear/templates/:
#   spec/: prd.md, architecture.md, epic-shard.md
#   plan/: phase-plan.md, fitness-function.md, research-brief.md
#   execute/: task-commit.md, deviation-log.md, checkpoint.md
